ts upon social histories and relationships and documents how residents of some sectors of Mexico construct their histories through performance. Festival dances and, sometimes, professional staged dances point to a continuing negotiation among Native American, Spanish, African, and other ethnic identities within the evolving nation of Mexico. These performances embody the mobile histories of ethnic encounters because each dance includes a spectrum of characters based upon local situations and historical memories.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aBlackszMexico. 0aDancezMexicoxAfrican influences. 0aNational characteristics, Mexican. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Black Studies (Global).2bisacsh1 aJackson, George O.1 aPellicer, José Manuel.1 aVinson, Ben, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVinson, Ben.40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292784772423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292784772/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK